<h5>10.1.1 Random experiment, sample space, and events</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>A six-sided die is rolled. Describe the random experiment, write the sample space, and define the following events: $A$ = "obtaining an even number", $B$ = "obtaining a number greater than 4", $A \cap B$, $A \cup B$, and $\bar{A}$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1 – Random experiment.</strong><br />
Rolling a six-sided die is a random experiment because the outcome cannot be predicted with certainty before it is performed.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 – Sample space.</strong><br />
$$\Omega = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3 – Define the events.</strong><br />
- $A$ = "obtaining an even number" $= {2, 4, 6}$<br />
- $B$ = "obtaining a number greater than 4" $= {5, 6}$</p>
<p><strong>Step 4 – Operations with events.</strong><br />
- $A \cap B = {2,4,6} \cap {5,6} = {6}$ (numbers that are both even and greater than 4)<br />
- $A \cup B = {2,4,5,6}$ (numbers that are even or greater than 4, or both)<br />
- $\bar{A} = \Omega \setminus A = {1,3,5}$ (odd numbers)</p>
<p><strong>Step 5 – Verification using the inclusion-exclusion formula.</strong><br />
$$|A \cup B| = |A| + |B| - |A \cap B| = 3 + 2 - 1 = 4 \checkmark$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A card is drawn from a Spanish deck of 40 cards. Write the reduced sample space by suit and define: $A$ = "card from the gold suit (oros)", $B$ = "card with number ≤ 3". Calculate $A \cap B$ and $A \cup B$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The sample space has 40 elements (10 cards × 4 suits). Using compact notation: $A = {1_\text{or}, 2_\text{or}, 3_\text{or}, 4_\text{or}, 5_\text{or}, 6_\text{or}, 7_\text{or}, 8_\text{or}, 9_\text{or}, 10_\text{or}}$ (10 elements); $B$ contains cards 1, 2, and 3 of each suit, that is, 12 elements. $A \cap B = {1_\text{or}, 2_\text{or}, 3_\text{or}}$ (3 elements, gold cards with number ≤ 3). $A \cup B$ has $10 + 12 - 3 = 19$ elements.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A coin is tossed three times. Write the complete sample space and indicate how many elements the event $C$ = "obtaining exactly two heads" has.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\Omega = {HHH, HHT, HTH, THH, HTT, THT, TTH, TTT}$, where H = heads and T = tails. $|\Omega| = 2^3 = 8$. $C = {HHT, HTH, THH}$, therefore $|C| = 3$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a class there are 30 students: 18 study physics, 14 study chemistry, and 8 study both. A student is chosen at random. Define $F$ = "studies physics" and $Q$ = "studies chemistry". Calculate $|F \cup Q|$, $|\overline{F \cup Q}|$, and check whether $F$ and $Q$ are mutually exclusive events.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $|F \cup Q| = |F| + |Q| - |F \cap Q| = 18 + 14 - 8 = 24$. The number of students who study at least one of the two subjects is 24, so $|\overline{F \cup Q}| = 30 - 24 = 6$ students study neither. Since $|F \cap Q| = 8 \neq 0$, the events are <strong>not</strong> mutually exclusive.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In an experiment, a 12-sided die is rolled. Define $A$ = "multiple of 3", $B$ = "multiple of 4", $C$ = "prime number". Calculate $A \cap B$, $B \cap C$, and $(A \cup B) \cap C$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\Omega = {1,2,...,12}$. $A = {3,6,9,12}$, $B = {4,8,12}$, $C = {2,3,5,7,11}$. $A \cap B = {12}$ (multiple of both 3 and 4, i.e. multiple of 12). $B \cap C = \emptyset$ (no multiple of 4 is prime in ${1,...,12}$). $A \cup B = {3,4,6,8,9,12}$; $(A \cup B) \cap C = {3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A hospital records the results of two diagnostic tests, $P_1$ and $P_2$, applied to 200 patients. Of them, 120 tested positive in $P_1$, 90 tested positive in $P_2$, and 50 tested positive in both tests.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) How many patients tested positive in at least one test?<br />
   b) How many tested positive only in $P_1$?<br />
   c) How many did not test positive in any test?<br />
   d) Describe in words the event $\overline{P_1 \cup P_2}$ and calculate its cardinality.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $|P_1 \cup P_2| = 120 + 90 - 50 = 160$ patients.<br />
b) Only in $P_1$: $|P_1| - |P_1 \cap P_2| = 120 - 50 = 70$ patients.<br />
c) $|\overline{P_1 \cup P_2}| = 200 - 160 = 40$ patients did not test positive in either test.<br />
d) $\overline{P_1 \cup P_2}$ = "the patient did not test positive in either of the two tests". Cardinality: 40.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A 6-sided die is rolled. Event $A$ = "even number" and $B$ = "number greater than 3". How many elements does $A \cup B$ have?</li>
<li>a) 3</li>
<li>b) 4</li>
<li>c) 5</li>
<li>d) 6</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> $A = {2,4,6}$, $B = {4,5,6}$. $A \cup B = {2,4,5,6}$, which has 4 elements.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $\Omega$ has 10 elements, $|A| = 6$ and $|B| = 5$ and $A$ and $B$ are mutually exclusive, how many elements does $\overline{A \cup B}$ have?</li>
<li>a) 0</li>
<li>b) 1</li>
<li>c) 9</li>
<li>d) 11</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> Since $A \cap B = \emptyset$, $|A \cup B| = 6 + 5 = 11$... but $|\Omega| = 10$, which would make it impossible to have $|A|+|B|=11$ if they are mutually exclusive with $|\Omega|=10$. Adjusting the statement to be compatible: $|A \cup B| \leq 10$. If $|A \cap B| = 1$, $|A \cup B| = 10$, $|\overline{A \cup B}| = 0$. <strong>Note for the student:</strong> in the case $|A|=6$, $|B|=5$ and $A,B$ disjoint within $\Omega$ of 10 elements, $|A \cup B|=11 &gt; 10$, which is impossible; in a corrected example with $|A|=4$, $|B|=5$, disjoint: $|\overline{A \cup B}|= 10-9=1$. Answer: <strong>b) 1</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
