<h5>10.1.2 Kolmogorov's Axioms</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Verify that the following function defines a probability on $\Omega = {a, b, c, d}$: $P({a}) = 0{,}3$, $P({b}) = 0{,}2$, $P({c}) = 0{,}4$, $P({d}) = 0{,}1$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Kolmogorov's three axioms are:
1. $P(A) \geq 0$ for every event $A$.
2. $P(\Omega) = 1$.
3. If $A \cap B = \emptyset$, then $P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B)$ (additivity for mutually exclusive events).</p>
<p><strong>Checking Axiom 1:</strong> $0{,}3 \geq 0$, $0{,}2 \geq 0$, $0{,}4 \geq 0$, $0{,}1 \geq 0$. ✓</p>
<p><strong>Checking Axiom 2:</strong>
$$P(\Omega) = P({a}) + P({b}) + P({c}) + P({d}) = 0{,}3 + 0{,}2 + 0{,}4 + 0{,}1 = 1{,}0 \checkmark$$</p>
<p><strong>Checking Axiom 3:</strong> The elementary events ${a}, {b}, {c}, {d}$ are pairwise disjoint, and $P({a,b}) = P({a}) + P({b}) = 0{,}5$. ✓</p>
<p>We conclude that it <strong>does define a probability</strong> on $\Omega$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given $\Omega = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}$ with $P({1}) = P({2}) = 0{,}1$, $P({3}) = 0{,}3$, $P({4}) = x$, $P({5}) = 0{,}2$. Determine $x$ so that $P$ is a valid probability.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> By Axiom 2: $0{,}1 + 0{,}1 + 0{,}3 + x + 0{,}2 = 1 \Rightarrow 0{,}7 + x = 1 \Rightarrow x = 0{,}3$. Since $x &gt; 0$, all three axioms are satisfied.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Can $P(A) = 1{,}2$ hold for some event? Justify your answer using the axioms.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> No. Axiom 1 requires $P(A) \geq 0$ and Axiom 2 implies $P(A) \leq P(\Omega) = 1$ (by monotonicity). Therefore $0 \leq P(A) \leq 1$ for every event $A$, and $1{,}2 &gt; 1$ violates this condition.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given an experiment with $\Omega = {e_1, e_2, e_3, e_4}$, it is known that $P(e_2) = 2P(e_1)$, $P(e_3) = 3P(e_1)$, and $P(e_4) = 4P(e_1)$. Calculate $P(e_1)$ and the probabilities of all elementary events.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(e_1) + 2P(e_1) + 3P(e_1) + 4P(e_1) = 1 \Rightarrow 10P(e_1) = 1 \Rightarrow P(e_1) = \frac{1}{10} = 0{,}1$. Therefore: $P(e_2) = 0{,}2$, $P(e_3) = 0{,}3$, $P(e_4) = 0{,}4$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Check which of the following functions is <strong>not</strong> a probability on $\Omega = {a, b, c}$ and explain which axiom it violates: (I) $P(a)=0{,}5,\ P(b)=-0{,}1,\ P(c)=0{,}6$; (II) $P(a)=0{,}5,\ P(b)=0{,}3,\ P(c)=0{,}3$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> (I) violates <strong>Axiom 1</strong> because $P(b) = -0{,}1 &lt; 0$. (II) violates <strong>Axiom 2</strong> because $0{,}5 + 0{,}3 + 0{,}3 = 1{,}1 \neq 1$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Two random experiments are defined. In experiment A, the sample space is $\Omega = {e_1, e_2, e_3, e_4, e_5}$ with probabilities proportional to their indices (that is, $P(e_k) = c \cdot k$).</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate the constant $c$.<br />
   b) Calculate $P({e_2, e_4})$ and $P({e_3, e_4, e_5})$.<br />
   c) Let $A = {e_1, e_3, e_5}$ and $B = {e_2, e_4}$. Are $A$ and $B$ mutually exclusive? Calculate $P(A \cup B)$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $\sum_{k=1}^{5} ck = c(1+2+3+4+5) = 15c = 1 \Rightarrow c = \dfrac{1}{15}$.<br />
b) $P({e_2, e_4}) = \dfrac{2}{15} + \dfrac{4}{15} = \dfrac{6}{15} = \dfrac{2}{5}$.<br />
$P({e_3, e_4, e_5}) = \dfrac{3+4+5}{15} = \dfrac{12}{15} = \dfrac{4}{5}$.<br />
c) $A \cap B = \emptyset$ (they share no elements), so they are <strong>mutually exclusive</strong>. $P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) = \dfrac{1+3+5}{15} + \dfrac{2+4}{15} = \dfrac{9}{15} + \dfrac{6}{15} = 1$. Indeed $A \cup B = \Omega$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If $P(A) = 0{,}6$ and $A, B$ are mutually exclusive with $P(A \cup B) = 0{,}9$, what is $P(B)$?</li>
<li>a) 0,54</li>
<li>b) 0,3</li>
<li>c) 1,5</li>
<li>d) Cannot be determined</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> By additivity: $P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) \Rightarrow 0{,}9 = 0{,}6 + P(B) \Rightarrow P(B) = 0{,}3$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Which of the following statements is a direct consequence of Kolmogorov's axioms?</li>
<li>a) $P(\emptyset) = 1$</li>
<li>b) $P(\bar{A}) = 1 + P(A)$</li>
<li>c) $P(\bar{A}) = 1 - P(A)$</li>
<li>d) $P(A \cup B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> It follows from $A \cup \bar{A} = \Omega$ (disjoint), so $P(A) + P(\bar{A}) = 1$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>10.1.3 Properties derived from the axioms</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Given $P(A) = 0{,}5$, $P(B) = 0{,}4$, and $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}2$, calculate: $P(\bar{A})$, $P(\bar{B})$, $P(A \cup B)$, $P(\overline{A \cup B})$, and $P(A \cap \bar{B})$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Complement:</strong>
$$P(\bar{A}) = 1 - P(A) = 1 - 0{,}5 = 0{,}5$$
$$P(\bar{B}) = 1 - P(B) = 1 - 0{,}4 = 0{,}6$$</p>
<p><strong>Union (inclusion-exclusion formula):</strong>
$$P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0{,}5 + 0{,}4 - 0{,}2 = 0{,}7$$</p>
<p><strong>Complement of the union (De Morgan):</strong>
$$P(\overline{A \cup B}) = 1 - P(A \cup B) = 1 - 0{,}7 = 0{,}3$$</p>
<p><strong>Difference $A \setminus B$ (only in $A$, not in $B$):</strong>
$$P(A \cap \bar{B}) = P(A) - P(A \cap B) = 0{,}5 - 0{,}2 = 0{,}3$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>$P(A) = 0{,}7$. Calculate $P(\bar{A})$ and $P(\bar{A} \cup A)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\bar{A}) = 1 - 0{,}7 = 0{,}3$. $P(\bar{A} \cup A) = P(\Omega) = 1$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>$P(A) = 0{,}4$, $P(B) = 0{,}5$, $P(A \cup B) = 0{,}7$. Calculate $P(A \cap B)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> From the inclusion-exclusion formula: $P(A \cap B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cup B) = 0{,}4 + 0{,}5 - 0{,}7 = 0{,}2$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Prove that $P(A \cap \bar{B}) = P(A) - P(A \cap B)$ using the axioms. Then calculate $P(A \cap \bar{B})$ if $P(A) = 0{,}6$ and $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}15$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $A = (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap \bar{B})$ and these two sets are disjoint (if $x \in A\cap B$ then $x \notin \bar{B}$). By additivity: $P(A) = P(A \cap B) + P(A \cap \bar{B}) \Rightarrow P(A \cap \bar{B}) = P(A) - P(A \cap B) = 0{,}6 - 0{,}15 = 0{,}45$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Given $P(A) = 0{,}5$, $P(B) = 0{,}3$, $P(C) = 0{,}4$, $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}1$, $P(A \cap C) = 0{,}2$, $P(B \cap C) = 0{,}15$, and $P(A \cap B \cap C) = 0{,}05$, calculate $P(A \cup B \cup C)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A \cup B \cup C) = P(A)+P(B)+P(C)-P(A\cap B)-P(A\cap C)-P(B\cap C)+P(A\cap B\cap C)$ $= 0{,}5+0{,}3+0{,}4-0{,}1-0{,}2-0{,}15+0{,}05 = 0{,}80$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a group of 100 students, 55 play football ($F$), 40 play basketball ($B$), and 20 play both sports. A student is chosen at random.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate $P(F \cup B)$.<br />
   b) Calculate the probability of playing only football.<br />
   c) Calculate the probability of playing neither sport.<br />
   d) Can it be stated that $F$ and $B$ are incompatible events? Justify.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $P(F) = 0{,}55$, $P(B) = 0{,}40$, $P(F \cap B) = 0{,}20$.<br />
$P(F \cup B) = 0{,}55 + 0{,}40 - 0{,}20 = \mathbf{0{,}75}$.<br />
b) $P(F \cap \bar{B}) = P(F) - P(F\cap B) = 0{,}55 - 0{,}20 = \mathbf{0{,}35}$.<br />
c) $P(\overline{F \cup B}) = 1 - 0{,}75 = \mathbf{0{,}25}$.<br />
d) No, because $P(F \cap B) = 0{,}20 \neq 0$; there are 20 students who play both sports, so they are <strong>compatible</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If $P(A) = 0{,}6$, $P(B) = 0{,}4$, and $P(A \cup B) = 0{,}8$, what is $P(A \cap B)$?</li>
<li>a) 0,24</li>
<li>b) 0,2</li>
<li>c) 1,0</li>
<li>d) 0,1</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}6 + 0{,}4 - 0{,}8 = 0{,}2$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The monotonicity property states that if $A \subseteq B$, then:</li>
<li>a) $P(A) \geq P(B)$</li>
<li>b) $P(A) = P(B)$</li>
<li>c) $P(A) \leq P(B)$</li>
<li>d) $P(A) \cdot P(B) = 1$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> If $A \subseteq B$, then $B = A \cup (B \setminus A)$ with disjoint parts, so $P(B) = P(A) + P(B \setminus A) \geq P(A)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>10.1.4 Venn diagrams: representation and calculation of probabilities</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>In a survey of 200 people, 110 consume product $X$, 80 consume product $Y$, and 40 consume both. Represent the situation in a Venn diagram and calculate the probability that a randomly chosen person consumes exactly one of the two products.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1 – Calculate the regions of the Venn diagram.</strong><br />
- Only $X$: $110 - 40 = 70$ people<br />
- Only $Y$: $80 - 40 = 40$ people<br />
- Both ($X \cap Y$): $40$ people<br />
- Neither: $200 - (70 + 40 + 40) = 200 - 150 = 50$ people</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 – Venn diagram (description).</strong></p>
<pre><code>    |------ 200 people ------|
    |  50  | 70 |X∩Y=40| 40 |  
    |       |     X    |  Y  |
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Step 3 – Calculate the required probability.</strong><br />
"Exactly one of the two" = (only $X$) $\cup$ (only $Y$):
$$P(\text{exactly one}) = \frac{70 + 40}{200} = \frac{110}{200} = 0{,}55$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a Venn diagram with $P(A) = 0{,}5$, $P(B) = 0{,}3$, and $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}1$, draw the diagram and indicate the value of each region.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Regions: only $A$: $0{,}5 - 0{,}1 = 0{,}4$; $A \cap B$: $0{,}1$; only $B$: $0{,}3 - 0{,}1 = 0{,}2$; neither: $1 - (0{,}4 + 0{,}1 + 0{,}2) = 0{,}3$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Using the diagram from the previous exercise, calculate $P(\bar{A} \cap \bar{B})$ (the "neither" region).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\bar{A} \cap \bar{B}) = P(\overline{A \cup B}) = 1 - P(A \cup B) = 1 - (0{,}5 + 0{,}3 - 0{,}1) = 1 - 0{,}7 = 0{,}3$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a medical study, 60% of patients have hypertension ($H$), 45% have diabetes ($D$), and 25% have both. Use a Venn diagram to calculate the probability that a patient has only one of the two conditions.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Only $H$: $0{,}60 - 0{,}25 = 0{,}35$; only $D$: $0{,}45 - 0{,}25 = 0{,}20$. $P(\text{exactly one}) = 0{,}35 + 0{,}20 = \mathbf{0{,}55}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In a factory, 30% of parts have a type $A$ defect, 20% have a type $B$ defect, and 5% have both defects. What percentage has no defect? What percentage has exactly one type of defect?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A \cup B) = 0{,}30 + 0{,}20 - 0{,}05 = 0{,}45$. No defect: $1 - 0{,}45 = \mathbf{0{,}55}$, that is 55%. Only $A$: $0{,}25$; only $B$: $0{,}15$. Exactly one defect: $0{,}25 + 0{,}15 = \mathbf{0{,}40}$ (40%).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a marketing campaign, two types of offer, $O_1$ and $O_2$, are sent to 500 customers. Responses to $O_1$: 180 customers; responses to $O_2$: 220 customers; responses to both: 60 customers.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Draw and fill in the Venn diagram indicating the number of customers in each region.<br />
   b) What is the probability that a randomly chosen customer responded to exactly one offer?<br />
   c) What is the probability of having responded to $O_1$ but not $O_2$?<br />
   d) What is the probability of having responded to neither offer?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) Only $O_1$: $180 - 60 = 120$; Both: $60$; Only $O_2$: $220 - 60 = 160$; Neither: $500 - (120+60+160) = 160$.<br />
b) $P(\text{exactly one}) = \dfrac{120 + 160}{500} = \dfrac{280}{500} = \mathbf{0{,}56}$.<br />
c) $P(O_1 \cap \bar{O_2}) = \dfrac{120}{500} = \mathbf{0{,}24}$.<br />
d) $P(\text{neither}) = \dfrac{160}{500} = \mathbf{0{,}32}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a Venn diagram, $P(A) = 0{,}4$, $P(B) = 0{,}35$, $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}15$. What is $P(\bar{A} \cap B)$?</li>
<li>a) 0,20</li>
<li>b) 0,35</li>
<li>c) 0,15</li>
<li>d) 0,05</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: a)</strong> $P(\bar{A} \cap B) = P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0{,}35 - 0{,}15 = 0{,}20$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If the regions of the Venn diagram for $A$ and $B$ (within $\Omega$) are: only $A = 0{,}3$; $A \cap B = 0{,}2$; only $B = 0{,}1$; neither = $0{,}4$. Then $P(A)$ equals:</li>
<li>a) 0,3</li>
<li>b) 0,5</li>
<li>c) 0,2</li>
<li>d) 0,6</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> $P(A) = P(\text{only } A) + P(A \cap B) = 0{,}3 + 0{,}2 = 0{,}5$.</p>
</blockquote>
