<h5>10.2.1 Multiplicative and additive counting principles</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>A restaurant menu offers 3 starters, 4 main courses, and 2 desserts. In how many different ways can a complete meal (one starter, one main course, and one dessert) be chosen?</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p>By the <strong>multiplication principle</strong>: if a task is performed in independent stages with $n_1$, $n_2$, ..., $n_k$ ways respectively, the total number of ways to complete all stages is $n_1 \cdot n_2 \cdots n_k$.</p>
<p>Stages:<br />
- Choice of starter: 3 ways<br />
- Choice of main course: 4 ways<br />
- Choice of dessert: 2 ways</p>
<p>Total: $3 \times 4 \times 2 = \mathbf{24}$ different meals.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A password consists of 2 letters (from a 27-letter alphabet) followed by 3 digits (from 0 to 9), without repetition. How many different passwords exist?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Letters without repetition: $27 \times 26 = 702$. Digits without repetition: $10 \times 9 \times 8 = 720$. Total: $702 \times 720 = \mathbf{505\,440}$ passwords.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A shop sells T-shirts in 5 colours, 3 sizes, and 2 styles (short/long sleeve). How many different models does it offer?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $5 \times 3 \times 2 = \mathbf{30}$ models.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A security code has 4 digits from 0 to 9. How many codes are there (a) with repetition and (b) without repetition? What percentage does the difference represent?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> (a) With repetition: $10^4 = 10\,000$. (b) Without repetition: $10 \times 9 \times 8 \times 7 = 5\,040$. Difference: $10\,000 - 5\,040 = 4\,960$, which represents $\dfrac{4960}{10000} = 49{,}6\%$ of the total.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In a mixed doubles tennis tournament, 6 men and 5 women participate. In how many ways can a mixed pair (one man and one woman) be formed?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $6 \times 5 = \mathbf{30}$ different pairs.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A company wants to assign 3 different tasks ($T_1$, $T_2$, $T_3$) to 3 different employees from a group of 8, so that each employee receives at most one task.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) In how many ways can this assignment be made?<br />
   b) If it is additionally required that $T_1$ always be done by the most senior employee, how many assignments are possible?<br />
   c) How many possible assignments are there if the three tasks are identical (only who works matters, not what they do)?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) Choose which employee does each task: $8 \times 7 \times 6 = \mathbf{336}$ ways (variations of 8 taken 3 at a time).<br />
b) $T_1$ is fixed (1 way). $T_2$: 7 remaining employees. $T_3$: 6. Total: $1 \times 7 \times 6 = \mathbf{42}$ ways.<br />
c) Now order does not matter: $\dbinom{8}{3} = \dfrac{8!}{3!\cdot 5!} = 56$ ways.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
