<h5>10.2.2 Combinations, variations, and permutations</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>A committee of 4 people is to be chosen from 10 candidates. In how many ways can the committee be formed if (a) all members have the same rank, (b) there is a president and three members?</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a) All with the same rank → Combinations</strong> (order does not matter):</p>
<p>$$C_{10,4} = \binom{10}{4} = \frac{10!}{4!\cdot 6!} = \frac{10 \times 9 \times 8 \times 7}{4 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} = \frac{5040}{24} = \mathbf{210} \text{ ways}$$</p>
<p><strong>(b) President and three members → Stages:</strong><br />
- Choose the president: 10 ways<br />
- Choose 3 members from the remaining 9 (without order): $\binom{9}{3} = 84$ ways<br />
- Total: $10 \times 84 = \mathbf{840}$ ways</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate: (a) $P_{5}^{5}$ (permutations of 5 elements), (b) $V_{8,3}$ (variations of 8 taken 3), (c) $\binom{7}{2}$ (combinations of 7 taken 2).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> (a) $5! = 120$. (b) $V_{8,3} = 8 \times 7 \times 6 = 336$. (c) $\dfrac{7!}{2! \cdot 5!} = \dfrac{7 \times 6}{2} = 21$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In how many ways can 6 people be seated in a row of 6 seats?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P_6 = 6! = 720$ ways.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a multiple-choice exam with 10 questions, a student must answer 7. In how many ways can the student choose which questions to answer?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\binom{10}{7} = \binom{10}{3} = \dfrac{10 \times 9 \times 8}{3!} = 120$ ways.</p>
</blockquote>
