</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A bag contains 10 numbered balls from 1 to 10. One is drawn at random. Calculate the probability that the number is prime or even.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Primes in ${1,...,10}$: ${2,3,5,7}$ (4 elements). Even numbers: ${2,4,6,8,10}$ (5 elements). Prime and even: ${2}$ (1 element). $P(\text{prime} \cup \text{even}) = \dfrac{4+5-1}{10} = \dfrac{8}{10} = \mathbf{0{,}8}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>2 cards are chosen simultaneously from a Spanish deck of 40 cards. What is the probability that both are from the cups suit?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Total ways to choose 2 cards: $\binom{40}{2} = 780$. Favourable ways (2 from cups, of which there are 10): $\binom{10}{2} = 45$. $P = \dfrac{45}{780} = \dfrac{3}{52} \approx \mathbf{0{,}0577}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a class of 30 students, 12 are women and 18 are men. 2 students are chosen at random to represent the class.</li>
