<h5>10.3.1 Definition of conditional probability: P(A|B)</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>In a factory, 2% of parts have a type $A$ defect, 3% have a type $B$ defect, and 0.5% have both defects. Calculate the probability that a part has defect $A$ given that it is already known to have defect $B$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Data: $P(A) = 0{,}02$, $P(B) = 0{,}03$, $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}005$.</p>
<p><strong>Conditional probability formula:</strong>
$$P(A \mid B) = \frac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)}$$</p>
<p>Substituting:
$$P(A \mid B) = \frac{0{,}005}{0{,}03} = \frac{5}{30} = \frac{1}{6} \approx \mathbf{0{,}1\overline{6}}$$</p>
<p><strong>Interpretation:</strong> Knowing that the part has defect $B$, the probability that it also has defect $A$ increases from 2% to 16.7%, which indicates a certain correlation between the two defects.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>$P(A) = 0{,}4$, $P(B) = 0{,}5$, $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}2$. Calculate $P(A \mid B)$ and $P(B \mid A)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A \mid B) = \dfrac{0{,}2}{0{,}5} = 0{,}4$. $P(B \mid A) = \dfrac{0{,}2}{0{,}4} = 0{,}5$.</p>
</blockquote>
