   b) Given that the first ball was red, what is the probability that the second is also red?<br />
   c) Calculate the probability that both balls are red.<br />
   d) Does the result of part (c) change if the drawing is done with replacement?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $P(R_1) = \dfrac{4}{10} = 0{,}4$.<br />
b) $P(R_2 \mid R_1) = \dfrac{3}{9} = \dfrac{1}{3} \approx 0{,}333$ (3 red balls remain among 9).<br />
c) $P(R_1 \cap R_2) = P(R_1) \cdot P(R_2 \mid R_1) = \dfrac{4}{10} \cdot \dfrac{3}{9} = \dfrac{12}{90} = \dfrac{2}{15} \approx 0{,}133$.<br />
d) With replacement: $P(R_1 \cap R_2) = \dfrac{4}{10} \cdot \dfrac{4}{10} = \dfrac{16}{100} = 0{,}16$. Yes, it changes (slightly higher because the urn is not "depleted").</p>
</blockquote>
