<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> $P(A \mid B)$ restricts the sample space to $B$, so that only cases where $B$ has occurred are considered.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>10.3.2 Multiplication rule: P(A ∩ B) = P(A|B)·P(B)</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>In a batch of 20 parts, 4 are defective. 2 parts are drawn at random without replacement. Calculate the probability that both parts are defective.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Let $D_1$ = "1st part defective" and $D_2$ = "2nd part defective".</p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> $P(D_1) = \dfrac{4}{20} = \dfrac{1}{5}$</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Given that the 1st is defective, there are 19 parts remaining, of which 3 are defective:
$$P(D_2 \mid D_1) = \frac{3}{19}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3 – Multiplication rule:</strong>
$$P(D_1 \cap D_2) = P(D_1) \cdot P(D_2 \mid D_1) = \frac{1}{5} \cdot \frac{3}{19} = \frac{3}{95} \approx \mathbf{0{,}0316}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>$P(B) = 0{,}6$ and $P(A \mid B) = 0{,}3$. Calculate $P(A \cap B)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A \cap B) = P(A \mid B) \cdot P(B) = 0{,}3 \times 0{,}6 = \mathbf{0{,}18}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A die is rolled twice. Calculate the probability of obtaining 6 in both rolls.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The rolls are independent. $P(6_1 \cap 6_2) = P(6_1) \cdot P(6_2) = \dfrac{1}{6} \cdot \dfrac{1}{6} = \dfrac{1}{36} \approx 0{,}028$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A box contains 3 red balls and 5 blue balls. 3 are drawn without replacement. Calculate the probability that all 3 are blue.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A_1) = \dfrac{5}{8}$, $P(A_2 \mid A_1) = \dfrac{4}{7}$, $P(A_3 \mid A_1 \cap A_2) = \dfrac{3}{6} = \dfrac{1}{2}$. $P = \dfrac{5}{8} \cdot \dfrac{4}{7} \cdot \dfrac{1}{2} = \dfrac{20}{112} = \dfrac{5}{28} \approx \mathbf{0{,}179}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A computer system has two firewalls in series. The first blocks 90% of attacks and the second blocks 95% of those that pass the first. What is the probability that an attack bypasses both?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\text{bypasses 1}) = 0{,}10$. $P(\text{bypasses 2} \mid \text{bypasses 1}) = 0{,}05$. $P(\text{bypasses both}) = 0{,}10 \times 0{,}05 = \mathbf{0{,}005}$ (0.5%).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a quality control process, parts pass through two inspections: $C_1$ and $C_2$. 5% of parts fail $C_1$. Of those that pass $C_1$, 3% fail $C_2$.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate the probability that a part passes both inspections.<br />
   b) Calculate the probability of failing exactly at $C_2$ (passed $C_1$ but failed $C_2$).<br />
   c) Calculate the probability of failing at least one of the two inspections.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
Let $S_1$ = "passes $C_1$": $P(S_1) = 0{,}95$; $F_1$ = "fails $C_1$": $P(F_1) = 0{,}05$.<br />
$P(S_2 \mid S_1) = 0{,}97$; $P(F_2 \mid S_1) = 0{,}03$.<br />
a) $P(S_1 \cap S_2) = 0{,}95 \times 0{,}97 = \mathbf{0{,}9215}$.<br />
b) $P(S_1 \cap F_2) = 0{,}95 \times 0{,}03 = \mathbf{0{,}0285}$.<br />
c) $P(\text{fails at least one}) = 1 - P(S_1 \cap S_2) = 1 - 0{,}9215 = \mathbf{0{,}0785}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If $P(A) = 0{,}5$, $P(B \mid A) = 0{,}4$, and $P(B \mid \bar{A}) = 0{,}2$, what is $P(A \cap B)$?</li>
<li>a) 0,20</li>
<li>b) 0,10</li>
<li>c) 0,30</li>
<li>d) 0,08</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: a)</strong> $P(A \cap B) = P(B \mid A) \cdot P(A) = 0{,}4 \times 0{,}5 = 0{,}20$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The general multiplication rule $P(A \cap B) = P(A \mid B) \cdot P(B)$ simplifies to $P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$ when:</li>
<li>a) $A$ and $B$ are incompatible</li>
<li>b) $A$ and $B$ are independent</li>
<li>c) $A \subset B$</li>
<li>d) $P(A) = P(B)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> If $A$ and $B$ are independent, then $P(A \mid B) = P(A)$, and the formula becomes $P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>10.3.3 Independence of events: definition and criterion</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>A die and a coin are tossed. Let $A$ = "rolling a 4 on the die" and $B$ = "getting heads on the coin". Check whether $A$ and $B$ are independent.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Independence criterion:</strong> $A$ and $B$ are independent if and only if $P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$.</p>
<p>$P(A) = \dfrac{1}{6}$, $P(B) = \dfrac{1}{2}$.</p>
<p>Since these are different experiments, the events are clearly independent. We verify:
$$P(A \cap B) = P(\text{rolling 4 and heads}) = \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{1}{12}$$</p>
<p>$$P(A) \cdot P(B) = \frac{1}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{1}{12}$$</p>
<p>Since $P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$, the events are <strong>independent</strong>. ✓</p>
<p><strong>Corollary:</strong> If $A$ and $B$ are independent, so are $A$ and $\bar{B}$, $\bar{A}$ and $B$, $\bar{A}$ and $\bar{B}$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>$P(A) = 0{,}4$, $P(B) = 0{,}5$, and $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}2$. Are $A$ and $B$ independent?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A) \cdot P(B) = 0{,}4 \times 0{,}5 = 0{,}2 = P(A \cap B)$. <strong>Yes, they are independent.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>$P(A) = 0{,}3$, $P(B) = 0{,}4$, and $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}15$. Are they independent?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A) \cdot P(B) = 0{,}12 \neq 0{,}15 = P(A \cap B)$. <strong>They are not independent</strong> (they are positively dependent events).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Prove that if $A$ and $B$ are independent, then $P(A \mid B) = P(A)$ (knowledge of $B$ does not alter the probability of $A$).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> If $A$ and $B$ are independent: $P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$. Then: $P(A \mid B) = \dfrac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)} = \dfrac{P(A) \cdot P(B)}{P(B)} = P(A)$. ✓</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Two independent medical tests are performed to detect a disease. Test $T_1$ has an 85% success rate and test $T_2$ has a 90% success rate. What is the probability that at least one detects the disease?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\text{neither detects}) = P(\bar{T_1}) \cdot P(\bar{T_2}) = 0{,}15 \times 0{,}10 = 0{,}015$. $P(\text{at least one}) = 1 - 0{,}015 = \mathbf{0{,}985}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Three electronic components $C_1$, $C_2$, and $C_3$ operate independently with failure probabilities $P(F_1) = 0{,}05$, $P(F_2) = 0{,}04$, and $P(F_3) = 0{,}02$. The system fails if at least one component fails.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate the probability that the system works correctly.<br />
   b) Calculate the probability that exactly component $C_1$ fails and the other two do not.<br />
   c) What is the probability that exactly two components fail?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $P(\text{system OK}) = P(\bar{F_1}) \cdot P(\bar{F_2}) \cdot P(\bar{F_3}) = 0{,}95 \times 0{,}96 \times 0{,}98 = \mathbf{0{,}8937}$.<br />
b) $P(F_1 \cap \bar{F_2} \cap \bar{F_3}) = 0{,}05 \times 0{,}96 \times 0{,}98 = \mathbf{0{,}04704}$.<br />
c) Exactly two fail: $P(F_1 F_2 \bar{F_3}) + P(F_1 \bar{F_2} F_3) + P(\bar{F_1} F_2 F_3)$<br />
$= 0{,}05 \times 0{,}04 \times 0{,}98 + 0{,}05 \times 0{,}96 \times 0{,}02 + 0{,}95 \times 0{,}04 \times 0{,}02$<br />
$= 0{,}00196 + 0{,}00096 + 0{,}00076 = \mathbf{0{,}00368}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If $A$ and $B$ are incompatible and both have positive probability, then:</li>
<li>a) They are independent</li>
<li>b) They cannot be independent</li>
<li>c) They are always independent if $P(A)+P(B)=1$</li>
<li>d) $P(A \cap B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> If they are incompatible, $P(A \cap B)=0$, but $P(A) \cdot P(B) &gt; 0$, so $P(A \cap B) \neq P(A) \cdot P(B)$: they are not independent.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $P(A) = 0{,}5$ and $A$ and $B$ are independent, what is $P(A \mid B)$?</li>
<li>a) 0,25</li>
<li>b) 0,5</li>
<li>c) Depends on $P(B)$</li>
<li>d) 1</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> By the definition of independence, $P(A \mid B) = P(A) = 0{,}5$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>10.3.4 Mutual independence of three or more events</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Events $A$, $B$, and $C$ are mutually independent if <strong>all</strong> of the following hold simultaneously:<br />
$P(A \cap B) = P(A)P(B)$, $P(A \cap C) = P(A)P(C)$, $P(B \cap C) = P(B)P(C)$ <strong>and</strong> $P(A \cap B \cap C) = P(A)P(B)P(C)$.</p>
<p>Given $P(A) = 0{,}5$, $P(B) = 0{,}4$, $P(C) = 0{,}3$, check whether they are mutually independent knowing that $P(A \cap B) = 0{,}2$, $P(A \cap C) = 0{,}15$, $P(B \cap C) = 0{,}12$, and $P(A \cap B \cap C) = 0{,}06$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>$P(A)P(B) = 0{,}5 \times 0{,}4 = 0{,}20 = P(A \cap B)$ ✓  </li>
<li>$P(A)P(C) = 0{,}5 \times 0{,}3 = 0{,}15 = P(A \cap C)$ ✓  </li>
<li>$P(B)P(C) = 0{,}4 \times 0{,}3 = 0{,}12 = P(B \cap C)$ ✓  </li>
<li>$P(A)P(B)P(C) = 0{,}5 \times 0{,}4 \times 0{,}3 = 0{,}06 = P(A \cap B \cap C)$ ✓</li>
</ul>
<p>All <strong>4 conditions</strong> are satisfied, so $A$, $B$, and $C$ are <strong>mutually independent</strong>.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Three coins are tossed. Let $A_i$ = "coin $i$ lands heads". Are $A_1$, $A_2$, and $A_3$ mutually independent?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A_i) = 1/2$ for all $i$. The tosses are independent. $P(A_1 \cap A_2) = 1/4 = P(A_1)P(A_2)$ ✓. Similarly for the other pairs. $P(A_1 \cap A_2 \cap A_3) = 1/8 = (1/2)^3$ ✓. <strong>Yes, they are mutually independent.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $A$, $B$, and $C$ are mutually independent with $P(A)=0{,}6$, $P(B)=0{,}5$, $P(C)=0{,}4$, calculate $P(A \cap B \cap C)$ and $P(A \cup B \cup C)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(A \cap B \cap C) = 0{,}6 \times 0{,}5 \times 0{,}4 = 0{,}12$. For the union, it is easier to use the complement: $P(\bar{A} \cap \bar{B} \cap \bar{C}) = 0{,}4 \times 0{,}5 \times 0{,}6 = 0{,}12$. $P(A \cup B \cup C) = 1 - 0{,}12 = \mathbf{0{,}88}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Example of events that are pairwise independent but NOT mutually independent (Bernstein's paradox): A coin is tossed twice. $A$ = "first heads", $B$ = "second heads", $C$ = "exactly one heads". Check that every pair is independent but $P(A \cap B \cap C) \neq P(A)P(B)P(C)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\Omega = {HH, HT, TH, TT}$ (equiprobable). $P(A) = P(B) = P(C) = 1/2$. $A \cap B = {HH}$: $P(A \cap B) = 1/4 = P(A)P(B)$ ✓. $A \cap C = {HT}$: $P(A \cap C) = 1/4 = P(A)P(C)$ ✓. $B \cap C = {TH}$: $P(B \cap C) = 1/4 = P(B)P(C)$ ✓. But $A \cap B \cap C = \emptyset$ (if both heads appear, there is not exactly one): $P(A \cap B \cap C) = 0 \neq 1/8 = P(A)P(B)P(C)$. <strong>They are not mutually independent.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In a system of three switches in parallel (the system works if at least one works), each switch fails independently with probability 0.1. Calculate the probability that the system fails.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The system fails only if all three switches fail. $P(\text{system fails}) = 0{,}1^3 = \mathbf{0{,}001}$ (0.1%).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A company manufactures chips that pass through three independent quality tests: $P_1$, $P_2$, and $P_3$. The probabilities of passing each test are 0.95, 0.92, and 0.98 respectively.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) What is the probability that a chip passes all three tests?<br />
   b) What is the probability of failing exactly test $P_2$?<br />
   c) What is the probability of passing at least two tests?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $P(S_1 S_2 S_3) = 0{,}95 \times 0{,}92 \times 0{,}98 = \mathbf{0{,}8557}$.<br />
b) Fails only $P_2$: $P(S_1 F_2 S_3) = 0{,}95 \times 0{,}08 \times 0{,}98 = \mathbf{0{,}07448}$.<br />
c) At least 2 tests passed = 2 passed + 3 passed:<br />
Exactly 2: $P(F_1 S_2 S_3) + P(S_1 F_2 S_3) + P(S_1 S_2 F_3)$<br />
$= 0{,}05 \times 0{,}92 \times 0{,}98 + 0{,}95 \times 0{,}08 \times 0{,}98 + 0{,}95 \times 0{,}92 \times 0{,}02$<br />
$= 0{,}04508 + 0{,}07448 + 0{,}01748 = 0{,}13704$.<br />
At least 2: $0{,}13704 + 0{,}8557 = \mathbf{0{,}99274}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>How many conditions must be verified for three events $A$, $B$, $C$ to be <strong>mutually independent</strong>?</li>
<li>a) 1</li>
<li>b) 2</li>
<li>c) 3</li>
<li>d) 4</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: d)</strong> There are 3 pairwise independence conditions plus 1 triple condition: <strong>4 conditions</strong> in total.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $A$ and $B$ are independent, which of the following statements is also true?</li>
<li>a) $\bar{A}$ and $B$ are dependent</li>
<li>b) $A$ and $\bar{B}$ are independent</li>
<li>c) $A$ and $B$ are incompatible</li>
<li>d) $P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> Independence is preserved when taking the complement of one or both events: $\bar{A}$ and $B$, $A$ and $\bar{B}$, $\bar{A}$ and $\bar{B}$ are also independent.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<hr />
<h5>10.4.1 Construction and interpretation of tree diagrams</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>An urn has 3 red balls and 2 blue balls. 2 balls are drawn <strong>without replacement</strong>. Build the complete tree diagram and calculate all branch probabilities.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Level 1 (1st draw):</strong>
- $P(R_1) = 3/5$<br />
- $P(A_1) = 2/5$</p>
<p><strong>Level 2 (2nd draw given the result of the 1st):</strong></p>
<p>If $R_1$ (4 balls remain: 2R, 2B):
- $P(R_2 \mid R_1) = 2/4 = 1/2$<br />
- $P(A_2 \mid R_1) = 2/4 = 1/2$</p>
<p>If $A_1$ (4 balls remain: 3R, 1B):
- $P(R_2 \mid A_1) = 3/4$<br />
- $P(A_2 \mid A_1) = 1/4$</p>
<p><strong>Path probabilities (multiplication rule):</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Path</th>
<th>Probability</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>$R_1 \cap R_2$</td>
<td>$\frac{3}{5} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{10}$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>$R_1 \cap A_2$</td>
<td>$\frac{3}{5} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{10}$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>$A_1 \cap R_2$</td>
<td>$\frac{2}{5} \cdot \frac{3}{4} = \frac{6}{20} = \frac{3}{10}$</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>$A_1 \cap A_2$</td>
<td>$\frac{2}{5} \cdot \frac{1}{4} = \frac{2}{20} = \frac{1}{10}$</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> $\frac{3}{10} + \frac{3}{10} + \frac{3}{10} + \frac{1}{10} = \frac{10}{10} = 1$ ✓</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A coin is tossed and then a die is rolled. Build the tree and calculate the probability of getting heads and an even number.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Level 1: $P(H) = 1/2$, $P(T) = 1/2$. Level 2 (die, 3 even numbers out of 6): $P(\text{even}) = 1/2$. $P(\text{heads and even}) = P(H) \cdot P(\text{even}) = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{1}{4}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A box has 2 red balls and 3 green balls. One is drawn, the colour is recorded, and it is returned (with replacement). Then another is drawn. Calculate the probability of obtaining two balls of the same colour.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> With replacement, the probabilities do not change. $P(RR) = \frac{2}{5} \cdot \frac{2}{5} = \frac{4}{25}$. $P(GG) = \frac{3}{5} \cdot \frac{3}{5} = \frac{9}{25}$. $P(\text{same colour}) = \frac{4}{25} + \frac{9}{25} = \frac{13}{25} = \mathbf{0{,}52}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a production process, 40% of parts are of type $A$ and 60% are of type $B$. 5% of type $A$ parts are defective and 2% of type $B$ parts are defective. A part is chosen at random. Build the tree and calculate the probability that it is defective.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(D) = P(D \mid A) \cdot P(A) + P(D \mid B) \cdot P(B) = 0{,}05 \times 0{,}40 + 0{,}02 \times 0{,}60 = 0{,}020 + 0{,}012 = \mathbf{0{,}032}$ (3.2%).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>An archer shoots two arrows. The probability of hitting with the first is 0.7. If the first hits, the probability of hitting with the second is 0.8; if the first misses, the probability of hitting with the second is 0.6. Calculate the probability of hitting exactly one arrow.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\text{hits 1st, misses 2nd}) = 0{,}7 \times 0{,}2 = 0{,}14$. $P(\text{misses 1st, hits 2nd}) = 0{,}3 \times 0{,}6 = 0{,}18$. $P(\text{exactly one}) = 0{,}14 + 0{,}18 = \mathbf{0{,}32}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A company receives components from two suppliers: 70% from supplier $P_1$ and 30% from supplier $P_2$. The percentage of defective parts from supplier $P_1$ is 4% and from supplier $P_2$ is 8%.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Build the complete tree diagram.<br />
   b) Calculate the probability that a randomly chosen part is defective.<br />
   c) If the part is defective, what is the probability that it came from $P_1$?<br />
   d) Which of the two suppliers produces more defective parts in absolute terms?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) Tree: $P_1 (0{,}7) \to D (0{,}04)$ and $\bar{D} (0{,}96)$; $P_2 (0{,}3) \to D (0{,}08)$ and $\bar{D} (0{,}92)$.<br />
b) $P(D) = 0{,}70 \times 0{,}04 + 0{,}30 \times 0{,}08 = 0{,}028 + 0{,}024 = \mathbf{0{,}052}$.<br />
c) $P(P_1 \mid D) = \dfrac{0{,}028}{0{,}052} = \dfrac{28}{52} = \dfrac{7}{13} \approx \mathbf{0{,}538}$.<br />
d) $P_1$ contributes $0{,}028$ and $P_2$ contributes $0{,}024$ of defective parts. Although $P_2$ has a higher defect rate (8%), it is $P_1$ that produces <strong>more defective parts</strong> in total due to its higher supply volume.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a tree diagram, the sum of the probabilities of all complete paths (leaves) must be:</li>
<li>a) Equal to the number of branches</li>
<li>b) Equal to 1</li>
<li>c) Equal to 0</li>
<li>d) Equal to the probability of the most likely event</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> The complete paths form a partition of the sample space, so their probabilities must sum to 1.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In a two-level tree with events $A$ and $B$ at the first level and $C$ and $D$ at the second, the probability of the path $A \to C$ is:</li>
<li>a) $P(A) + P(C)$</li>
<li>b) $P(A) \cdot P(C)$</li>
<li>c) $P(A) \cdot P(C \mid A)$</li>
<li>d) $P(C \mid A) / P(A)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> The multiplication rule states that the path probability is $P(A \cap C) = P(A) \cdot P(C \mid A)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>10.4.2 Calculating compound probabilities using trees</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>In a multiple-choice exam with 3 questions, each question has 4 options and only one is correct. A student who does not know the answer chooses at random. It is known that the student knows 70% of the topics. Calculate the probability that the student answers the first question correctly.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1 – Define events:</strong><br />
- $S$ = "knows the answer": $P(S) = 0{,}7$, $P(\bar{S}) = 0{,}3$<br />
- $C$ = "answers correctly"</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 – Conditional probabilities:</strong><br />
- If they know: $P(C \mid S) = 1$ (answers with certainty)<br />
- If they do not know: $P(C \mid \bar{S}) = 1/4 = 0{,}25$ (chooses at random)</p>
<p><strong>Step 3 – Total probability theorem:</strong>
$$P(C) = P(C \mid S) \cdot P(S) + P(C \mid \bar{S}) \cdot P(\bar{S})$$
$$P(C) = 1 \times 0{,}7 + 0{,}25 \times 0{,}3 = 0{,}7 + 0{,}075 = \mathbf{0{,}775}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A box is chosen from two: box 1 has 3 red balls and 2 blue balls; box 2 has 1 red and 4 blue balls. The probability of choosing box 1 is 0.4. Calculate the probability of drawing a red ball.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(R) = P(R \mid C_1) \cdot P(C_1) + P(R \mid C_2) \cdot P(C_2) = \frac{3}{5} \times 0{,}4 + \frac{1}{5} \times 0{,}6 = 0{,}24 + 0{,}12 = \mathbf{0{,}36}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>An athlete trains 5 days a week. If they trained the day before, the probability of winning a competition is 0.8; if they did not train, it is 0.4. They train 70% of days. Calculate the probability of winning.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\text{wins}) = 0{,}8 \times 0{,}7 + 0{,}4 \times 0{,}3 = 0{,}56 + 0{,}12 = \mathbf{0{,}68}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A medical test can give a positive (+) or negative (−) result. If the patient has the disease, $P(+ \mid E) = 0{,}95$. If they do not have it, $P(+ \mid \bar{E}) = 0{,}08$. The prevalence of the disease is 1%. Calculate the probability of obtaining a positive result.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(E) = 0{,}01$. $P(+) = 0{,}95 \times 0{,}01 + 0{,}08 \times 0{,}99 = 0{,}0095 + 0{,}0792 = \mathbf{0{,}0887}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Three machines produce screws. Machine $M_1$ produces 50%, $M_2$ 30%, and $M_3$ 20%. The percentages of defective screws are 2%, 3%, and 5% respectively. Calculate the probability of drawing a defective screw.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(D) = 0{,}02 \times 0{,}50 + 0{,}03 \times 0{,}30 + 0{,}05 \times 0{,}20 = 0{,}010 + 0{,}009 + 0{,}010 = \mathbf{0{,}029}$ (2.9%).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a production plant, parts are manufactured in three shifts. The morning shift ($M$) produces 40% of parts, the afternoon shift ($T$) 35%, and the night shift ($N$) 25%. The percentages of defective parts are 1%, 2%, and 4% respectively.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Build the tree diagram with all branches and probabilities.<br />
   b) Calculate the probability that a randomly chosen part is defective.<br />
   c) If a defective part is chosen, from which shift is it most likely to come?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) First level: $M (0{,}40)$, $T (0{,}35)$, $N (0{,}25)$. Second level: each shift branches into $D$ and $\bar{D}$.<br />
b) $P(D) = 0{,}01 \times 0{,}40 + 0{,}02 \times 0{,}35 + 0{,}04 \times 0{,}25 = 0{,}004 + 0{,}007 + 0{,}010 = \mathbf{0{,}021}$.<br />
c) $P(M \mid D) = \frac{0{,}004}{0{,}021} \approx 0{,}190$; $P(T \mid D) = \frac{0{,}007}{0{,}021} \approx 0{,}333$; $P(N \mid D) = \frac{0{,}010}{0{,}021} \approx 0{,}476$. The defective part is most likely to come from the <strong>night shift</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a tree with two groups $G_1$ (probability 0.6) and $G_2$ (probability 0.4), and within each group event $A$ has probabilities $P(A \mid G_1) = 0{,}3$ and $P(A \mid G_2) = 0{,}5$, what is $P(A)$?</li>
<li>a) 0,38</li>
<li>b) 0,40</li>
<li>c) 0,35</li>
<li>d) 0,15</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: a)</strong> $P(A) = 0{,}3 \times 0{,}6 + 0{,}5 \times 0{,}4 = 0{,}18 + 0{,}20 = 0{,}38$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The compound probability of a path in a three-level tree $A \to B \to C$ is calculated as:</li>
<li>a) $P(A) + P(B \mid A) + P(C \mid B)$</li>
<li>b) $P(A) \cdot P(B) \cdot P(C)$</li>
<li>c) $P(A) \cdot P(B \mid A) \cdot P(C \mid A \cap B)$</li>
<li>d) $P(C \mid A \cap B) / P(A)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> The generalised multiplication rule: $P(A \cap B \cap C) = P(A) \cdot P(B \mid A) \cdot P(C \mid A \cap B)$.</p>
</blockquote>
