<h5>10.4.3 Contingency tables: construction and interpretation</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>In a survey of 500 people, they are asked about their gender (Male/Female) and transport preference (Car/Public transport). The results are: 180 males prefer the car, 70 males prefer public transport, 100 females prefer the car, and 150 females prefer public transport. Build the complete contingency table.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1 – Fill in the table:</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th></th>
<th>Car</th>
<th>Public Transport</th>
<th>Total</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Male</td>
<td>180</td>
<td>70</td>
<td><strong>250</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Female</td>
<td>100</td>
<td>150</td>
<td><strong>250</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Total</strong></td>
<td><strong>280</strong></td>
<td><strong>220</strong></td>
<td><strong>500</strong></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Step 2 – Verify the totals:</strong> $180+70 = 250$, $100+150 = 250$, $180+100 = 280$, $70+150 = 220$. Grand total: $280+220 = 500$ ✓</p>
<p><strong>Step 3 – Calculate marginal and joint probabilities:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>$P(\text{Male}) = 250/500 = 0{,}5$  </li>
<li>$P(\text{Car}) = 280/500 = 0{,}56$  </li>
<li>$P(\text{Male and Car}) = 180/500 = 0{,}36$</li>
</ul>
