<h5>10.4.4 Extracting marginal, joint, and conditional probabilities from tables</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Given the following contingency table on 200 employees (gender and department):</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th></th>
<th>Production</th>
<th>Sales</th>
<th>Administration</th>
<th>Total</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Male</td>
<td>60</td>
<td>40</td>
<td>20</td>
<td>120</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Female</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>20</td>
<td>80</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Total</td>
<td>90</td>
<td>70</td>
<td>40</td>
<td>200</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
