<h5>10.5.1 Partition of the sample space: complete system of events</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Check that the events $A_1 = {1,2}$, $A_2 = {3,4}$, and $A_3 = {5,6}$ form a partition of $\Omega = {1,2,3,4,5,6}$ (the sample space when rolling a die).</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p>A complete system of events (partition) must satisfy:
1. The events are pairwise disjoint (incompatible).
2. Their union is $\Omega$ (they are exhaustive).</p>
<p><strong>Check 1 (disjointness):</strong>
- $A_1 \cap A_2 = {1,2} \cap {3,4} = \emptyset$ ✓<br />
- $A_1 \cap A_3 = {1,2} \cap {5,6} = \emptyset$ ✓<br />
- $A_2 \cap A_3 = {3,4} \cap {5,6} = \emptyset$ ✓</p>
<p><strong>Check 2 (exhaustiveness):</strong>
$$A_1 \cup A_2 \cup A_3 = {1,2,3,4,5,6} = \Omega \checkmark$$</p>
<p>They do form a <strong>partition</strong> of $\Omega$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Do the sets $A_1 = [0, 0{,}5)$, $A_2 = [0{,}5, 1]$ form a partition of the sample space $\Omega = [0,1]$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $A_1 \cap A_2 = \emptyset$ ✓. $A_1 \cup A_2 = [0,1] = \Omega$ ✓. <strong>Yes, they form a partition.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Indicate which of the following does <strong>not</strong> form a partition of $\Omega = {1,2,3,4,5}$: (a) ${1,2}, {3,4}, {5}$; (b) ${1,2}, {2,3,4}, {5}$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> (a) Yes it is a partition: disjoint and exhaustive ✓. (b) <strong>Not</strong> a partition because ${1,2} \cap {2,3,4} = {2} \neq \emptyset$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a factory, parts are classified as: severely defective ($D_G$), mildly defective ($D_L$), and correct ($C$). Explain why these three categories form a partition of the sample space and what condition their probabilities must satisfy.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> They are disjoint (a part cannot be both severely and mildly defective at once) and exhaustive (every part belongs to some category). Therefore they form a partition. The condition is $P(D_G) + P(D_L) + P(C) = 1$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Given the experiment "choose a number from 1 to 20", build a partition into 4 events according to the remainder when dividing by 4 ($R = 0, 1, 2, 3$). Calculate the probabilities of each event in the partition.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $A_0 = {4,8,12,16,20}$ (5 elements), $A_1 = {1,5,9,13,17}$ (5 elements), $A_2 = {2,6,10,14,18}$ (5 elements), $A_3 = {3,7,11,15,19}$ (5 elements). $P(A_i) = 5/20 = 1/4$ for each $i$. Sum: $4 \times 1/4 = 1$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In an industrial process control, products are classified by quality level: quality A (30%), quality B (45%), and quality C (25%).</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Verify that these three categories form a partition of the sample space.<br />
   b) If it is known that 2% of quality A products are rejected, 5% of quality B products, and 15% of quality C products, what is the probability of rejection for a randomly chosen product? (Anticipation of the total probability theorem.)</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) They are disjoint (a product belongs to exactly one quality level) and $0{,}30 + 0{,}45 + 0{,}25 = 1$ ✓. They form a partition.<br />
b) $P(R) = 0{,}02 \times 0{,}30 + 0{,}05 \times 0{,}45 + 0{,}15 \times 0{,}25 = 0{,}006 + 0{,}0225 + 0{,}0375 = \mathbf{0{,}066}$ (6.6%).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>For $A_1, A_2, A_3$ to form a partition of the sample space, the following must hold:</li>
<li>a) Only that they are disjoint</li>
<li>b) Only that they are exhaustive ($A_1 \cup A_2 \cup A_3 = \Omega$)</li>
<li>c) That they are disjoint and exhaustive</li>
<li>d) That they have equal probability</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> A partition requires that the events be pairwise incompatible (disjoint) <strong>and</strong> that their union be the complete sample space (exhaustive).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If ${A_1, A_2, A_3}$ is a partition of $\Omega$, then:</li>
<li>a) $P(A_1) = P(A_2) = P(A_3)$</li>
<li>b) $P(A_1) + P(A_2) + P(A_3) = 1$</li>
<li>c) $A_1 \subset A_2 \subset A_3$</li>
<li>d) $P(A_1 \cup A_2) = 0$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> Being disjoint and covering all of $\Omega$, the sum of their probabilities is $P(\Omega) = 1$.</p>
</blockquote>
