<h5>10.5.3 Bayes' theorem: statement and application to posterior probabilities</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Using the data from the worked example in section 10.5.2, calculate the probability that a defective part was manufactured on line $L_2$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Data reminder:</strong>
$P(L_1)=0{,}5$, $P(L_2)=0{,}3$, $P(L_3)=0{,}2$, $P(D \mid L_1)=0{,}02$, $P(D \mid L_2)=0{,}04$, $P(D \mid L_3)=0{,}06$, $P(D) = 0{,}034$.</p>
<p><strong>Bayes' theorem:</strong>
$$P(L_2 \mid D) = \frac{P(D \mid L_2) \cdot P(L_2)}{P(D)}$$</p>
<p>Substituting:
$$P(L_2 \mid D) = \frac{0{,}04 \times 0{,}3}{0{,}034} = \frac{0{,}012}{0{,}034} = \frac{12}{34} = \frac{6}{17} \approx \mathbf{0{,}353}$$</p>
<p><strong>Bayes summary table:</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Line</th>
<th>$P(L_i)$</th>
<th>$P(D \mid L_i)$</th>
<th>$P(D \cap L_i)$</th>
<th>$P(L_i \mid D)$</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>$L_1$</td>
<td>0,5</td>
<td>0,02</td>
<td>0,010</td>
<td>0,010/0,034 ≈ 0,294</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>$L_2$</td>
<td>0,3</td>
<td>0,04</td>
<td>0,012</td>
<td>0,012/0,034 ≈ 0,353</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>$L_3$</td>
<td>0,2</td>
<td>0,06</td>
<td>0,012</td>
<td>0,012/0,034 ≈ 0,353</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Total</strong></td>
<td><strong>1</strong></td>
<td></td>
<td><strong>0,034</strong></td>
<td><strong>1</strong></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Using the data from basic exercise 1 in section 10.5.2 (urns), calculate the probability that the red ball came from urn $U_1$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(U_1 \mid R) = \dfrac{P(R \mid U_1) \cdot P(U_1)}{P(R)} = \dfrac{(4/10) \times 0{,}5}{0{,}55} = \dfrac{0{,}20}{0{,}55} = \dfrac{4}{11} \approx \mathbf{0{,}364}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>$P(A) = 0{,}4$, $P(B \mid A) = 0{,}7$, $P(B \mid \bar{A}) = 0{,}2$. Calculate $P(A \mid B)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(B) = 0{,}7 \times 0{,}4 + 0{,}2 \times 0{,}6 = 0{,}28 + 0{,}12 = 0{,}40$. $P(A \mid B) = \dfrac{0{,}7 \times 0{,}4}{0{,}40} = \dfrac{0{,}28}{0{,}40} = \mathbf{0{,}7}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In the diagnostic test example (section 10.5.2, intermediate exercise 4), calculate the probability that a patient with a positive test really has the disease.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(E) = 0{,}02$, $P(+ \mid E) = 0{,}92$, $P(+) = 0{,}0674$. $P(E \mid +) = \dfrac{0{,}92 \times 0{,}02}{0{,}0674} = \dfrac{0{,}0184}{0{,}0674} \approx \mathbf{0{,}273}$ (27.3%). This result illustrates the test paradox: although the test is quite accurate, with low prevalence most positives are false positives.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A lie detector is correct 90% of the time when a person is lying and 95% when they are telling the truth (i.e. only 5% of truthful people appear as liars). It is known that 10% of suspects lie. If the detector indicates "lie", what is the probability that the person is actually lying?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(\text{lies}) = 0{,}10$, $P(+ \mid \text{lies}) = 0{,}90$, $P(+ \mid \text{truthful}) = 0{,}05$. $P(+) = 0{,}90 \times 0{,}10 + 0{,}05 \times 0{,}90 = 0{,}09 + 0{,}045 = 0{,}135$. $P(\text{lies} \mid +) = \dfrac{0{,}09}{0{,}135} = \dfrac{2}{3} \approx \mathbf{0{,}667}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A pharmaceutical laboratory manufactures a drug in two plants: plant $A$ produces 60% of lots and plant $B$ 40%. The probability that a lot from plant $A$ fails quality control is 0.03; for plant $B$ it is 0.06.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate the probability that a randomly chosen lot fails the inspection.<br />
   b) A lot fails the inspection. Calculate the probability that it comes from each plant.<br />
   c) Which plant contributes more to rejected lots? Which has the higher rejection rate?<br />
   d) If plant $B$ reduces its rejection rate to 3%, how does the overall rejection probability change?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $P(R) = 0{,}03 \times 0{,}60 + 0{,}06 \times 0{,}40 = 0{,}018 + 0{,}024 = \mathbf{0{,}042}$.<br />
b) $P(A \mid R) = \dfrac{0{,}018}{0{,}042} = \dfrac{3}{7} \approx \mathbf{0{,}429}$. $P(B \mid R) = \dfrac{0{,}024}{0{,}042} = \dfrac{4}{7} \approx \mathbf{0{,}571}$.<br />
c) Plant $B$ contributes more to rejections (57.1% of rejected lots come from $B$), and also has the higher rejection rate (6% vs 3%).<br />
d) $P(R)' = 0{,}03 \times 0{,}60 + 0{,}03 \times 0{,}40 = 0{,}018 + 0{,}012 = \mathbf{0{,}030}$. Rejection would drop from 4.2% to 3%.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Bayes' theorem allows us to calculate:</li>
<li>a) The total probability of an event</li>
<li>b) The posterior probability $P(A_i \mid B)$ knowing prior and conditional probabilities</li>
<li>c) The probability of the union of two events</li>
<li>d) The independence between events</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> Bayes updates prior probabilities $P(A_i)$ ("a priori") with information from the observed event $B$, yielding "posterior" probabilities $P(A_i \mid B)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In Bayes' theorem, if $P(A_1 \mid B) = P(A_1)$, then:</li>
<li>a) $B$ is the most probable event</li>
<li>b) $A_1$ and $B$ are independent</li>
<li>c) $A_1$ and $B$ are incompatible</li>
<li>d) $P(B) = 0$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> If the posterior probability equals the prior, event $B$ has provided no information about $A_1$: they are independent.</p>
</blockquote>
