<h5>10.5.4 Applications of Bayes' theorem in real contexts: diagnostic tests and reliability</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>A diagnostic test for detecting a disease has the following characteristics:
- Sensitivity (probability of positive given the disease is present): 96%<br />
- Specificity (probability of negative given the disease is absent): 98%<br />
- Prevalence of the disease in the population: 0.5%</p>
<p>Calculate the <strong>positive predictive value</strong> (probability of having the disease given a positive result).</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Data:</strong>
- $P(E) = 0{,}005$ (prevalence)<br />
- $P(\bar{E}) = 0{,}995$<br />
- $P(+ \mid E) = 0{,}96$ (sensitivity)<br />
- $P(- \mid \bar{E}) = 0{,}98$ (specificity) $\Rightarrow P(+ \mid \bar{E}) = 0{,}02$</p>
<p><strong>Step 1 – Total probability of a positive result:</strong>
$$P(+) = P(+ \mid E) \cdot P(E) + P(+ \mid \bar{E}) \cdot P(\bar{E})$$
$$P(+) = 0{,}96 \times 0{,}005 + 0{,}02 \times 0{,}995 = 0{,}0048 + 0{,}0199 = 0{,}0247$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 – Positive predictive value (Bayes):</strong>
$$PPV = P(E \mid +) = \frac{P(+ \mid E) \cdot P(E)}{P(+)} = \frac{0{,}0048}{0{,}0247} \approx \mathbf{0{,}194}$$</p>
<p><strong>Interpretation:</strong> Only 19.4% of those who test positive actually have the disease. Although the test is very accurate, the low prevalence means that most positives are <strong>false positives</strong>. This is the <strong>prevalence effect</strong> in medical diagnosis.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If the prevalence were 10% (instead of 0.5%) in the previous worked example, keeping sensitivity and specificity the same, what would the PPV be?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(+) = 0{,}96 \times 0{,}10 + 0{,}02 \times 0{,}90 = 0{,}096 + 0{,}018 = 0{,}114$. $PPV = 0{,}096/0{,}114 \approx \mathbf{0{,}842}$ (84.2%). With higher prevalence, the PPV increases dramatically.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A test has sensitivity 90% and specificity 95%. The prevalence is 20%. Calculate the probability that a negative test result truly means the absence of disease (negative predictive value).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(-) = P(- \mid E) \cdot P(E) + P(- \mid \bar{E}) \cdot P(\bar{E}) = 0{,}10 \times 0{,}20 + 0{,}95 \times 0{,}80 = 0{,}02 + 0{,}76 = 0{,}78$. $NPV = P(\bar{E} \mid -) = \dfrac{0{,}95 \times 0{,}80}{0{,}78} = \dfrac{0{,}76}{0{,}78} \approx \mathbf{0{,}974}$ (97.4%).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a factory producing integrated circuits, 3% of chips are defective. An automatic detector correctly identifies 99% of defective chips and incorrectly classifies 2% of good chips as defective. Calculate the probability that a chip flagged as defective is actually defective.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(D)=0{,}03$, $P(+ \mid D)=0{,}99$, $P(+ \mid \bar{D})=0{,}02$. $P(+)=0{,}99\times 0{,}03+0{,}02\times 0{,}97=0{,}0297+0{,}0194=0{,}0491$. $P(D \mid +)=\dfrac{0{,}0297}{0{,}0491}\approx\mathbf{0{,}605}$ (60.5%).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>An airport security system detects 98% of real prohibited items. However, it triggers a false alarm for 0.5% of passengers with no prohibited items. If it is estimated that 1 in every 10,000 passengers carries a prohibited item, calculate the probability that a passenger who triggers the alarm is actually carrying the item.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(O)=0{,}0001$, $P(A \mid O)=0{,}98$, $P(A \mid \bar{O})=0{,}005$. $P(A)=0{,}98\times 0{,}0001+0{,}005\times 0{,}9999=0{,}000098+0{,}004999=0{,}005097$. $P(O \mid A)=\dfrac{0{,}000098}{0{,}005097}\approx\mathbf{0{,}0192}$ (1.9%). This result justifies the need for additional checks.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>An insurance company classifies its clients into three risk profiles: low risk ($B$, 50%), medium risk ($M$, 35%), and high risk ($A$, 15%). The probabilities that a client from each profile has a claim in a year are: $P(S \mid B) = 0{,}02$, $P(S \mid M) = 0{,}08$, and $P(S \mid A) = 0{,}25$.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate the probability that a randomly chosen client has a claim.<br />
   b) If a client has had a claim, what is the probability that they belong to each risk profile?<br />
   c) A client has a claim. The company wants to reclassify them. Which profile should they be assigned to with the highest probability?<br />
   d) By how much does the overall claim probability change if high-risk clients increase from 15% to 25% (at the expense of low-risk clients)?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $P(S)=0{,}02\times 0{,}5+0{,}08\times 0{,}35+0{,}25\times 0{,}15=0{,}010+0{,}028+0{,}0375=\mathbf{0{,}0755}$.<br />
b) $P(B \mid S)=\dfrac{0{,}010}{0{,}0755}\approx 0{,}132$; $P(M \mid S)=\dfrac{0{,}028}{0{,}0755}\approx 0{,}371$; $P(A \mid S)=\dfrac{0{,}0375}{0{,}0755}\approx 0{,}497$.<br />
c) With probability ~49.7%, the client who had a claim is <strong>high risk</strong>: they should be reclassified as such.<br />
d) New distribution: $B=40\%$, $M=35\%$, $A=25\%$. $P'(S)=0{,}02\times 0{,}40+0{,}08\times 0{,}35+0{,}25\times 0{,}25=0{,}008+0{,}028+0{,}0625=\mathbf{0{,}0985}$. Increases from 7.55% to 9.85%.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In medical diagnosis, the <strong>positive predictive value</strong> is:</li>
<li>a) $P(\text{disease})$</li>
<li>b) $P(\text{positive} \mid \text{disease})$</li>
<li>c) $P(\text{disease} \mid \text{positive})$</li>
<li>d) $P(\text{positive})$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> The PPV is the probability of having the disease given a positive test result, which is calculated using Bayes' theorem.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If the prevalence of a disease increases while keeping sensitivity and specificity of a test constant, the positive predictive value:</li>
<li>a) Decreases</li>
<li>b) Does not change</li>
<li>c) Increases</li>
<li>d) Depends only on the value of specificity</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> Higher prevalence means more real cases in the population, which increases the probability that a positive result is genuine. This can be demonstrated mathematically with Bayes' theorem.</p>
</blockquote>
