<h5>11.1.3 Expected value, variance, and standard deviation</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>A discrete random variable $X$ has the following probability distribution:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>$x$</th>
<th>0</th>
<th>1</th>
<th>2</th>
<th>3</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>$P(X=x)$</td>
<td>0,1</td>
<td>0,3</td>
<td>0,4</td>
<td>0,2</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Calculate the expected value $E(X)$, the variance $\text{Var}(X)$, and the standard deviation $\sigma(X)$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Expected value (mean):</strong>
$$E(X) = \sum x_i \cdot P(X=x_i) = 0(0{,}1)+1(0{,}3)+2(0{,}4)+3(0{,}2)$$
$$E(X) = 0 + 0{,}3 + 0{,}8 + 0{,}6 = \mathbf{1{,}7}$$</p>
<p><strong>$E(X^2)$:</strong>
$$E(X^2) = 0^2(0{,}1)+1^2(0{,}3)+2^2(0{,}4)+3^2(0{,}2) = 0+0{,}3+1{,}6+1{,}8 = 3{,}7$$</p>
<p><strong>Variance:</strong>
$$\text{Var}(X) = E(X^2) - [E(X)]^2 = 3{,}7 - (1{,}7)^2 = 3{,}7 - 2{,}89 = \mathbf{0{,}81}$$</p>
<p><strong>Standard deviation:</strong>
$$\sigma(X) = \sqrt{\text{Var}(X)} = \sqrt{0{,}81} = \mathbf{0{,}9}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>$X$ takes values 1, 2, 3 with equal probabilities $1/3$. Calculate $E(X)$ and $\text{Var}(X)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $E(X) = (1+2+3)/3 = \mathbf{2}$. $E(X^2) = (1+4+9)/3 = 14/3$. $\text{Var}(X) = 14/3 - 4 = 2/3 \approx \mathbf{0{,}667}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A coin is tossed: if heads, $X=2$; if tails, $X=-1$. Calculate $E(X)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $E(X) = 2 \times 0{,}5 + (-1) \times 0{,}5 = 1 - 0{,}5 = \mathbf{0{,}5}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In the dice game with $X$ = sum of two dice (values 2 to 12), the expected value is $E(X) = 7$. Calculate the variance using $E(X^2) = 54{,}\overline{8}$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\text{Var}(X) = E(X^2) - [E(X)]^2 = 54{,}\overline{8} - 49 = 5{,}\overline{8} \approx \mathbf{5{,}833}$. $\sigma \approx 2{,}415$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A company pays per part: if the part is perfect (probability 0.9) it earns 10 €; if it has a minor defect (prob. 0.08) it earns 5 €; if it has a major defect (prob. 0.02) it loses 20 €. Calculate the expected income per part.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $E(X) = 10(0{,}9)+5(0{,}08)+(-20)(0{,}02) = 9 + 0{,}4 - 0{,}4 = \mathbf{9}$ € per part.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>An insurance company offers home insurance at 300 € per year. The probabilities of a claim are: no damage (prob. 0.94, indemnification 0 €), minor damage (prob. 0.04, indemnification 1,000 €), moderate damage (prob. 0.015, indemnification 5,000 €), severe damage (prob. 0.005, indemnification 20,000 €).</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate the expected claim cost for the insurer.<br />
   b) Calculate the expected profit per policy.<br />
   c) Calculate the standard deviation of the claim cost.<br />
   d) Is the insurance price reasonable from an actuarial perspective?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $E(\text{claim}) = 0(0{,}94)+1000(0{,}04)+5000(0{,}015)+20000(0{,}005)$<br />
$= 0+40+75+100 = \mathbf{215}$ €.<br />
b) Expected profit = $300 - 215 = \mathbf{85}$ € per policy.<br />
c) $E(S^2) = 0+10^6(0{,}04)+25\times10^6(0{,}015)+400\times10^6(0{,}005) = 40000+375000+2000000 = 2415000$. $\text{Var} = 2415000 - 215^2 = 2415000-46225 = 2368775$. $\sigma = \sqrt{2368775} \approx \mathbf{1539}$ €.<br />
d) The price of 300 € covers the expected cost (215 €) with a margin of 85 € to cover expenses and profit. However, the high standard deviation (1539 €) indicates that the insurer needs a large portfolio for risks to offset each other (law of large numbers).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If $E(X) = 3$ and $E(X^2) = 13$, then $\text{Var}(X)$ equals:</li>
<li>a) 4</li>
<li>b) 10</li>
<li>c) 9</li>
<li>d) 16</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: a)</strong> $\text{Var}(X) = E(X^2) - [E(X)]^2 = 13 - 9 = 4$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The standard deviation of a random variable measures:</li>
<li>a) The most probable value</li>
<li>b) The spread or variability of the distribution around the mean</li>
<li>c) The skewness of the distribution</li>
<li>d) The median of the distribution</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> The standard deviation $\sigma = \sqrt{\text{Var}(X)}$ quantifies how much the values of the variable are dispersed around the mean $E(X)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>11.1.4 Properties of expected value and variance: E(aX+b) and Var(aX+b)</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Given a variable $X$ with $E(X) = 4$ and $\text{Var}(X) = 9$, calculate $E(2X-3)$, $\text{Var}(2X-3)$, and $\sigma(2X-3)$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Properties:</strong>
- $E(aX+b) = a \cdot E(X) + b$<br />
- $\text{Var}(aX+b) = a^2 \cdot \text{Var}(X)$</p>
<p><strong>Expected value:</strong>
$$E(2X-3) = 2 \cdot E(X) - 3 = 2 \times 4 - 3 = 8 - 3 = \mathbf{5}$$</p>
<p><strong>Variance:</strong>
$$\text{Var}(2X-3) = 2^2 \cdot \text{Var}(X) = 4 \times 9 = \mathbf{36}$$</p>
<p><strong>Standard deviation:</strong>
$$\sigma(2X-3) = \sqrt{36} = \mathbf{6}$$</p>
<p>Note that the constant $b = -3$ does <strong>not</strong> affect the variance (it only shifts the distribution without changing its spread).</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>$E(X) = 5$, $\text{Var}(X) = 4$. Calculate $E(3X+1)$ and $\text{Var}(3X+1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $E(3X+1) = 3(5)+1 = \mathbf{16}$. $\text{Var}(3X+1) = 9 \times 4 = \mathbf{36}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Exam grades follow a distribution with $\mu = 5$ and $\sigma = 1{,}5$. The teacher transforms grades using $Y = 0{,}8X + 2$. What are the mean and standard deviation of $Y$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $E(Y) = 0{,}8(5)+2 = \mathbf{6}$. $\sigma(Y) = 0{,}8 \times 1{,}5 = \mathbf{1{,}2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Derive the property $\text{Var}(aX+b) = a^2 \text{Var}(X)$ from the definition $\text{Var}(X) = E[(X-\mu)^2]$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Let $Y = aX+b$. $E(Y) = a\mu+b$. $\text{Var}(Y) = E[(Y-E(Y))^2] = E[(aX+b-a\mu-b)^2] = E[(a(X-\mu))^2] = E[a^2(X-\mu)^2] = a^2 E[(X-\mu)^2] = a^2\text{Var}(X)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A machine produces parts with length $X$ of mean 100 mm and standard deviation 2 mm. If it is calibrated so that the new length is $Y = 1{,}05X - 5$, what are the new mean and standard deviation?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $E(Y) = 1{,}05(100)-5 = 105-5 = \mathbf{100}$ mm (the mean is maintained). $\sigma(Y) = 1{,}05 \times 2 = \mathbf{2{,}1}$ mm (slightly greater dispersion).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Service times (in minutes) at an emergency unit follow a distribution with $E(T) = 15$ and $\text{Var}(T) = 25$. The hospital wants to transform the times to a standardised scale $Z = (T - 15)/5$ to facilitate comparison.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Calculate $E(Z)$ and $\text{Var}(Z)$.<br />
   b) Calculate the probability (in general terms) that a standardised time falls between $-1$ and $1$ using Chebyshev's inequality ($P(|X - \mu| \leq k\sigma) \geq 1 - 1/k^2$).<br />
   c) If the transformation $W = 2T + 10$ (new scale in scaled seconds) is applied, calculate $E(W)$ and $\sigma(W)$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $E(Z) = E!\left(\frac{T-15}{5}\right) = \frac{E(T)-15}{5} = \frac{15-15}{5} = \mathbf{0}$. $\text{Var}(Z) = \frac{\text{Var}(T)}{25} = \frac{25}{25} = \mathbf{1}$.<br />
b) $k=1$ in Chebyshev: $P(|Z| \leq 1) \geq 1-1/1 = 0$. This only gives a trivial bound. With $k=2$: $P(|Z| \leq 2) \geq 1-1/4 = 3/4 = 75\%$.<br />
c) $E(W) = 2(15)+10 = \mathbf{40}$. $\sigma(W) = 2\sigma(T) = 2\times5 = \mathbf{10}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If $\text{Var}(X) = 4$ and $Y = -3X + 7$, then $\text{Var}(Y)$ equals:</li>
<li>a) -12</li>
<li>b) 12</li>
<li>c) 36</li>
<li>d) 43</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> $\text{Var}(Y) = (-3)^2 \text{Var}(X) = 9 \times 4 = 36$. The constant 7 does not affect the variance.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $E(X) = 2$ and $Y = X - E(X) = X - 2$ is defined, then $E(Y)$ equals:</li>
<li>a) 2</li>
<li>b) -2</li>
<li>c) 0</li>
<li>d) 4</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> $E(Y) = E(X-2) = E(X)-2 = 2-2 = 0$. A centred variable always has expected value 0.</p>
</blockquote>
