<h5>11.4.1 Conditions for the approximation: large n, np ≥ 5 and n(1−p) ≥ 5</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>For each of the following binomial distributions, state whether the conditions are met to approximate by a normal distribution and, if so, write the parameters of the approximating normal:<br />
(a) $X \sim B(200,\; 0{,}3)$<br />
(b) $X \sim B(30,\; 0{,}04)$<br />
(c) $X \sim B(100,\; 0{,}06)$</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step solution:</strong></p>
<p>The conditions for the approximation $B(n,p) \approx N(np,\; \sqrt{np(1-p)})$ are:
- $n$ large (in practice, $n \geq 30$).
- $np \geq 5$ and $n(1-p) \geq 5$.</p>
<p><strong>(a) $B(200, 0{,}3)$:</strong>
- $np = 200 \times 0{,}3 = 60 \geq 5$ ✓
- $n(1-p) = 200 \times 0{,}7 = 140 \geq 5$ ✓
- Can be approximated: $X \approx N(60,\; \sqrt{200\times0{,}3\times0{,}7}) = N(60,\; \sqrt{42}) \approx N(60,\; 6{,}48)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b) $B(30, 0{,}04)$:</strong>
- $np = 30 \times 0{,}04 = 1{,}2 &lt; 5$ ✗
- The condition $np \geq 5$ is <strong>not satisfied</strong>. Cannot be approximated by the normal.</p>
<p><strong>(c) $B(100, 0{,}06)$:</strong>
- $np = 100 \times 0{,}06 = 6 \geq 5$ ✓
- $n(1-p) = 100 \times 0{,}94 = 94 \geq 5$ ✓
- Can be approximated: $\mu = 6$, $\sigma = \sqrt{100\times0{,}06\times0{,}94} = \sqrt{5{,}64} \approx 2{,}37$.<br />
  $X \approx N(6,\; 2{,}37)$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Check whether $X \sim B(50, 0{,}2)$ can be approximated by a normal. If so, write the approximating normal distribution.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $np=50\times0{,}2=10 \geq 5$ ✓; $n(1-p)=50\times0{,}8=40 \geq 5$ ✓. Can be approximated: $X \approx N(10,\; \sqrt{50\times0{,}2\times0{,}8}) = N(10,\; \sqrt{8}) \approx N(10,\; 2{,}83)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Can $X \sim B(20, 0{,}1)$ be approximated by a normal? Justify.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $np=20\times0{,}1=2 &lt; 5$. The condition $np \geq 5$ is <strong>not satisfied</strong>. It <strong>cannot</strong> be adequately approximated by the normal in this case.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In an electoral poll, 45% of voters support party A. 400 people are surveyed. Can the normal approximation be used? Find $\mu$ and $\sigma$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $np=400\times0{,}45=180 \geq 5$ ✓; $n(1-p)=400\times0{,}55=220 \geq 5$ ✓. Yes. $\mu=180$, $\sigma=\sqrt{400\times0{,}45\times0{,}55}=\sqrt{99}\approx9{,}95$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A company manufactures components with a 2% defect rate. How many components must be produced at minimum for the normal approximation to be valid?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We need $np \geq 5 \Rightarrow n\times0{,}02 \geq 5 \Rightarrow n \geq 250$. Also $n(1-p)=0{,}98n \geq 5$ holds for any $n \geq 6$. Therefore at least $\mathbf{n = 250}$ components are needed.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>At a food processing plant, 8% of containers have some defect. A batch of 120 containers is inspected.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Is the approximation of the binomial by the normal valid? Justify by checking the conditions.<br />
   b) Write the approximating normal distribution with its parameters $\mu$ and $\sigma$.<br />
   c) If the defect rate dropped to 3% with the same batch size, could the normal approximation be used?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $np=120\times0{,}08=9{,}6 \geq 5$ ✓; $n(1-p)=120\times0{,}92=110{,}4 \geq 5$ ✓. The approximation <strong>is valid</strong>.<br />
b) $\mu=9{,}6$; $\sigma=\sqrt{120\times0{,}08\times0{,}92}=\sqrt{8{,}832}\approx2{,}972$. Approximating distribution: $N(9{,}6,\; 2{,}972)$.<br />
c) $np=120\times0{,}03=3{,}6 &lt; 5$. The normal approximation would <strong>not be valid</strong> at that defect rate.</p>
</blockquote>
