<h5>11.4.2 Yates' continuity correction</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Let $X \sim B(100,\; 0{,}4)$. Use the normal approximation with Yates' correction to calculate $P(X = 40)$, $P(X \leq 38)$ and $P(X \geq 45)$.</p>
<p><strong>Step-by-step solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Approximating distribution:</strong> $\mu = 100\times0{,}4=40$; $\sigma=\sqrt{100\times0{,}4\times0{,}6}=\sqrt{24}\approx4{,}899$.</p>
<p><strong>Yates' correction (continuity correction):</strong> When approximating a discrete distribution by a continuous one, we substitute:
- $P(X = k) \approx P(k-0{,}5 \leq Y \leq k+0{,}5)$
- $P(X \leq k) \approx P(Y \leq k+0{,}5)$
- $P(X \geq k) \approx P(Y \geq k-0{,}5)$</p>
<p><strong>$P(X=40)$:</strong>
$$P(X=40) \approx P(39{,}5 \leq Y \leq 40{,}5)$$
$$z_1 = \frac{39{,}5-40}{4{,}899} = \frac{-0{,}5}{4{,}899} \approx -0{,}102; \quad z_2 = \frac{40{,}5-40}{4{,}899} \approx 0{,}102$$
$$P \approx \Phi(0{,}102)-\Phi(-0{,}102) = 2\Phi(0{,}102)-1 \approx 2(0{,}5406)-1 = \mathbf{0{,}0812}$$</p>
<p><strong>$P(X \leq 38)$:</strong>
$$P(X \leq 38) \approx P(Y \leq 38{,}5)$$
$$z = \frac{38{,}5-40}{4{,}899} = \frac{-1{,}5}{4{,}899} \approx -0{,}306$$
$$P \approx \Phi(-0{,}306) = 1-\Phi(0{,}306) \approx 1-0{,}6203 = \mathbf{0{,}3797}$$</p>
<p><strong>$P(X \geq 45)$:</strong>
$$P(X \geq 45) \approx P(Y \geq 44{,}5)$$
$$z = \frac{44{,}5-40}{4{,}899} \approx \frac{4{,}5}{4{,}899} \approx 0{,}919$$
$$P \approx 1-\Phi(0{,}919) \approx 1-0{,}8212 = \mathbf{0{,}1788}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let $X \sim B(80, 0{,}5) \approx N(40, \sqrt{20})$ with $\sigma \approx 4{,}472$. With Yates' correction, write the probability $P(X \leq 42)$ as $P(Y \leq ?)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(X \leq 42) \approx P(Y \leq 42{+}0{,}5) = P(Y \leq 42{,}5)$. Standardising: $z=(42{,}5-40)/4{,}472 \approx 0{,}559$. $P(Y \leq 42{,}5) \approx \Phi(0{,}56) \approx \mathbf{0{,}7123}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>With $X \sim B(120, 0{,}3) \approx N(36, \sqrt{25{,}2})$ ($\sigma \approx 5{,}02$), apply Yates' correction to calculate $P(X \geq 40)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(X \geq 40) \approx P(Y \geq 39{,}5)$. $z=(39{,}5-36)/5{,}02\approx0{,}697$. $P(Y \geq 39{,}5) \approx 1-\Phi(0{,}70) \approx 1-0{,}7580 = \mathbf{0{,}2420}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>35% of customers at an online shop abandon their cart without purchasing. In 200 visits, use the normal approximation with Yates' correction to calculate $P(X \leq 65)$. ($\mu=70$, $\sigma=\sqrt{200\times0{,}35\times0{,}65}=\sqrt{45{,}5}\approx6{,}745$.)</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(X \leq 65) \approx P(Y \leq 65{,}5)$. $z=(65{,}5-70)/6{,}745\approx-0{,}667$. $P(Y \leq 65{,}5)\approx\Phi(-0{,}667)=1-\Phi(0{,}667)\approx1-0{,}7476=\mathbf{0{,}2524}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Explain why Yates' correction improves the approximation of the binomial by the normal compared to not applying it.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The binomial distribution is discrete (integer values), while the normal is continuous. When calculating $P(X=k)$ without correction, the point $k$ (with zero measure in the normal) is approximated. Yates' correction extends the interval to $[k-0{,}5, k+0{,}5]$, which has positive area under the normal curve, achieving a better approximation of the discrete probability. In general, it reduces the systematic error of the approximation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><em>(EVAU Madrid style)</em> A medication has 70% efficacy: it cures 70% of the patients who take it. It is administered to 150 patients.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Define $X$ and verify that it can be approximated by the normal.<br />
   b) Write the approximating normal distribution.<br />
   c) With Yates' correction, calculate $P(X \geq 110)$. [$\Phi(0{,}94)\approx0{,}8264$]<br />
   d) With Yates' correction, calculate $P(100 \leq X \leq 115)$. [$\Phi(0{,}53)\approx0{,}7019$; $\Phi(1{,}47)\approx0{,}9292$]</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $X \sim B(150,\;0{,}7)$. $np=105\geq5$ ✓; $n(1-p)=45\geq5$ ✓. Approximation valid.<br />
b) $\mu=105$; $\sigma=\sqrt{150\times0{,}7\times0{,}3}=\sqrt{31{,}5}\approx5{,}612$. $X\approx N(105,\;5{,}612)$.<br />
c) $P(X\geq110)\approx P(Y\geq109{,}5)$. $z=(109{,}5-105)/5{,}612\approx4{,}5/5{,}612\approx0{,}802$. $P\approx1-\Phi(0{,}80)\approx1-0{,}7881=\mathbf{0{,}2119}$.<br />
<em>(Using $z\approx0{,}80$ as the table may differ slightly; with $z\approx0{,}94$: if $z=(110-0{,}5-105)/5{,}612\approx0{,}802$, the answer is $\approx0{,}211$.)</em><br />
d) $P(100 \leq X \leq 115) \approx P(99{,}5 \leq Y \leq 115{,}5)$.<br />
$z_1=(99{,}5-105)/5{,}612\approx-0{,}98$; $z_2=(115{,}5-105)/5{,}612\approx1{,}87$.<br />
$P\approx\Phi(1{,}87)-\Phi(-0{,}98)=0{,}9693-(1-0{,}8365)=0{,}9693-0{,}1635=\mathbf{0{,}8058}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Yates' correction consists of:</li>
<li>a) Adding 1 to the value of $n$.</li>
<li>b) Extending the discrete interval by adding and subtracting 0.5 to use the continuous distribution.</li>
<li>c) Multiplying the probability by 0.5.</li>
<li>d) Dividing $\sigma$ by 2.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> Yates' correction adjusts for continuity by extending the interval by $\pm 0{,}5$ to improve the approximation of the discrete distribution by the continuous one.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To calculate $P(X = 50)$ with the normal approximation with Yates' correction, we use:</li>
<li>a) $P(Y \leq 50)$</li>
<li>b) $P(Y \leq 50{,}5)$</li>
<li>c) $P(49{,}5 \leq Y \leq 50{,}5)$</li>
<li>d) $P(50 \leq Y \leq 51)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> For a point probability, we apply the correction on both sides: $P(X=k) \approx P(k-0{,}5 \leq Y \leq k+0{,}5)$.</p>
</blockquote>
