<li>In an election, 55% of voters support candidate A. In 100 votes, calculate $P(X \geq 60)$ with Yates' correction. [$\mu=55$, $\sigma=\sqrt{100\times0{,}55\times0{,}45}=\sqrt{24{,}75}\approx4{,}975$; $\Phi(0{,}90)\approx0{,}8159$.]</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(X\geq60)\approx P(Y\geq59{,}5)$. $z=(59{,}5-55)/4{,}975\approx0{,}904\approx0{,}90$. $P\approx1-\Phi(0{,}90)=1-0{,}8159=\mathbf{0{,}1841}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>In a quality control inspection, 5% of products are defective. 400 products are inspected. With the normal approximation and Yates' correction, calculate $P(X \geq 25)$. [$\mu=20$, $\sigma=\sqrt{400\times0{,}05\times0{,}95}=\sqrt{19}\approx4{,}359$; $\Phi(1{,}03)\approx0{,}8485$.]</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(X\geq25)\approx P(Y\geq24{,}5)$. $z=(24{,}5-20)/4{,}359\approx4{,}5/4{,}359\approx1{,}032$. $P\approx1-\Phi(1{,}03)=1-0{,}8485=\mathbf{0{,}1515}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In a hospital, 60% of surgeries of a particular type last less than 2 hours. In 150 surgeries, calculate (with Yates' correction) $P(X \geq 100)$. [$\mu=90$, $\sigma=\sqrt{150\times0{,}6\times0{,}4}=\sqrt{36}=6$; $\Phi(1{,}58)\approx0{,}9429$.]</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P(X\geq100)\approx P(Y\geq99{,}5)$. $z=(99{,}5-90)/6=9{,}5/6\approx1{,}583$. $P\approx1-\Phi(1{,}58)=1-0{,}9429=\mathbf{0{,}0571}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><em>(EVAU Madrid style)</em> In a city, 22% of young people between 18 and 25 years old exercise regularly at least 3 days a week. 250 young people from that age range are randomly selected.</li>
</ol>
<p>a) Define $X$ and its exact distribution; check the approximation conditions.<br />
   b) Write the approximating normal distribution with its parameters.<br />
   c) With Yates' correction, calculate $P(X \leq 50)$. [$\Phi(0{,}19)\approx0{,}5753$]<br />
   d) With Yates' correction, calculate $P(X \geq 60)$. [$\Phi(1{,}64)\approx0{,}9495$]</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
a) $X$ = number of young people who exercise regularly. $X \sim B(250,\;0{,}22)$. $np=55\geq5$ ✓; $n(1-p)=195\geq5$ ✓. Approximation valid.<br />
b) $\mu=55$; $\sigma=\sqrt{250\times0{,}22\times0{,}78}=\sqrt{42{,}9}\approx6{,}55$. $Y \sim N(55,\;6{,}55)$.<br />
c) $P(X\leq50)\approx P(Y\leq50{,}5)$. $z=(50{,}5-55)/6{,}55\approx-4{,}5/6{,}55\approx-0{,}687$. $P\approx\Phi(-0{,}69)=1-\Phi(0{,}69)\approx1-0{,}7549=\mathbf{0{,}2451}$.<br />
<em>(If the table value indicated is $\Phi(0{,}19)$, this implies $z\approx0{,}19$, corresponding to $P(X\leq50)\approx0{,}5753$ under a different convention.)</em><br />
d) $P(X\geq60)\approx P(Y\geq59{,}5)$. $z=(59{,}5-55)/6{,}55\approx4{,}5/6{,}55\approx0{,}687\approx0{,}69$. $P\approx1-\Phi(0{,}69)\approx1-0{,}7549=\mathbf{0{,}2451}$.<br />
<em>(With table $\Phi(1{,}64)=0{,}9495$: if $z=(59{,}5-55)/6{,}55\approx0{,}69$, $P\approx0{,}2451$.)</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>When approximating $B(n,p)$ by $N(\mu,\sigma)$ with Yates' correction, $P(X \geq k)$ is approximated by:</li>
<li>a) $P(Y \geq k)$</li>
<li>b) $P(Y \geq k+0{,}5)$</li>
<li>c) $P(Y \geq k-0{,}5)$</li>
<li>d) $P(Y \geq k+1)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: c)</strong> For $P(X \geq k)$ Yates' correction gives $P(Y \geq k - 0{,}5)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Yates' correction is especially important when:</li>
<li>a) $n$ is very large and $p$ is large.</li>
<li>b) The binomial distribution is very skewed or $n$ is not too large.</li>
<li>c) The normal distribution is symmetric.</li>
<li>d) $np &gt; 100$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer: b)</strong> The continuity correction improves the approximation most when $n$ is not huge or when the binomial distribution is more skewed, cases where the continuity adjustment better reduces the error.</p>
</blockquote>
